The Nigeria Correctional Service (NCoS), formerly known as the Nigeria Prisons Service (NPS), has remained in the eye of the storm due to the growing trend of jailbreaks across Nigeria. Since October 2020 when hoodlums hijacked the #EndSARS protest to attack three Nigerian Correctional Service (NCoS) facilities in Edo and Ondo states, the country has continued to witness more incidents of prison breaks. Checks by The Nation show there have been more jailbreaks since the October 2020 incident. The latest attack occurred on July 6 when terrorists attacked the Medium Security Custodial Centre, Kuje, Abuja, adding to the growing list of jailbreaks in recent years.   Fed Govt: petrol scarcity will linger until full…     Kuje prison: 64 Boko Haram suspects escape after attack     Kuje: Day terrorists wreaked havoc   The Nation’s checks further revealed that on 24 June 2016, there was a jailbreak at the Kuje custodial facility. Two high-profile inmates escaped through the fence. Also, on August 29, 2016, there was an attempted jailbreak at the same facility   Prison attacks in Nigeria since 2020